# Testing and quality gates

## Test design

- Write tests against observable behavior and contracts, not incidental implementation details.
- Use the test pyramid appropriate to the system: fast unit tests, boundary/contract tests, integration tests with real dependencies where risk warrants, and focused end-to-end tests for critical journeys.
- Every bug fix MUST include a regression test that fails before the fix.
- Every authorization rule MUST include allowed and denied cases.
- Every parser/validator MUST include valid, malformed, boundary, oversized, ambiguous, and adversarial cases.
- Every state machine MUST test valid transitions, invalid transitions, idempotency, retries, and recovery.

## Deterministic tests

- Tests MUST control time, randomness, locale, timezone, filesystem paths, environment, network, and concurrency where relevant.
- NEVER use arbitrary sleeps for synchronization. Await observable conditions with explicit deadlines.
- Tests MUST be independent, order-insensitive, repeatable, parallel-safe, and self-cleaning.
- NEVER depend on production services or mutable third-party data in unit/CI tests.
- Use fixed seeds and report them on randomized failure.

## Testability

- Keep I/O, clock, randomness, process execution, network, persistence, and telemetry behind explicit boundaries.
- Dependency injection MUST remain narrow and purposeful; do not create a container merely to mock everything.
- Prefer in-memory fakes for stable domain contracts and real ephemeral dependencies for integration semantics.
- Avoid mocking private methods or third-party internals.

## Coverage

- Coverage is a risk signal, not proof. Do not write assertion-free tests to satisfy a percentage.
- Critical security, financial, state-transition, and data-integrity paths require branch coverage and negative-path coverage.
- New or changed code MUST not reduce repository coverage thresholds.
- Use mutation testing for high-risk logic when supported by the stack.

## Completion gates

Before declaring completion, run and report the applicable formatter, linter, type checker, unit tests, integration tests, contract tests, end-to-end tests, build, architecture checks, security scans, accessibility checks, and benchmarks. State any check not run and why.
